My sincerest apologies for not getting back to you sooner.  This has been the most hectic quarter I have experienced.  With this in mind, from purely an academic perspective (I am not clear if you are a for-profit or not-for-profit entity, and as a WA State employee, I am  not licensed or qualified to provide more than my academic opinion), I believe your website provides intended users with basic hints, tips, and strategies for helping entrepreneurs develop their web presence.  My first piece of advice is to always obtain permission to link with the SBA, SCORE, SBDC websites, all of which have hundreds/thousands of visitors looking for the type of advice you can provide (this will be particularly helpful if you are a non-profit entity).  Also, while there is a table of contents set of hyperlinks to expanded content on your pages, do you have a list of specific areas of consulting expertise you are willing to provide customers (if the examples you provided in the cascading page are your specific work...showcase it!)?  If so, perhaps using this as the first paragraph (hyperlinked to further content) to provide expanded content and further specific examples of your business model.  Additionally, while I am glad you cited your work at the bottom of the pages, it might be helpful to provide further information about these links (website names or source names hyperlinked for customers to explore), rather than simply website links.  Finally, if I were a potential customer looking for information and/or consulting, I would like to see a list and links to your satisfied customers, which illustrates the partnerships you have made, showcases your work, and further provides a network of customers for your clients.  Otherwise, I think the information you are providing with your site is solid, and provides users and clients with a broad overview of the business online environment.  Maybe one more area to explore would be how to target different user groups and demographics of potential website users (what 20 year olds versus 50 year olds are looking for from a website).  I hope you find these comments useful!

Correspondence Notes: Thank you for your correspondence addressed to the Honourable Kevin Flynn, Minister of Labour, which has been referred to me for response. The Ontario Ministry of Labourês role is to advance safe, fair and stable workplace practices that are essential to the social and economic well-being of the people of Ontario, Canada. The ministry sets, communicates and enforces workplace standards in the areas of occupational health and safety, employment rights and responsibilities, and labour relations. The matter you reference is outside the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Labour. However, the Government of Ontario has programs that assist and advise people on establishing small businesses; it also provides supports to established ones. The Ministry of Training, Colleges and Universities has information for entrepreneurs interested in starting a business. You can find useful information on its website at http://www.tcu.gov.on.ca/eng/career/entrepre.html. In addition, the Ministry of Economic Development, Employment and Infrastructure is responsible for Small Business Enterprise centres throughout Ontario. These centres provide helpful business advice, support and services to help people start or grow a business. You can locate the nearest centre to you at http://www.ontario.ca/business-and-economy/small-business-advice-support-services-regulations. Thank you again for writing and we wish you all the best in your endeavours. Yours truly,
